Here's a complete migration guide for your `EventProcessor`.

## Problems in .NET 8

| Issue | Severity |
|-------|----------|
| `Thread.Abort()` → throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` | **Build-breaking** |
| `Thread.Interrupt()` → obsolete (`SYSLIB0046` in .NET 9) | Warning / future-breaking |
| `ManualResetEvent.WaitOne()` not cancellation-aware | Cannot stop cleanly |
| Race condition: multiple fast `Enqueue` calls, only 1 dequeue per wake | **Latent bug** |

## Pattern Classification

- **Cancellable work loop** — `while(true)` → use `CancellationToken`
- **Blocking call interruption** — `WaitOne()` woken by `Interrupt` → use `WaitHandle.WaitAny` with `token.WaitHandle`

## Migrated Code (Direct — CancellationToken)

A 1:1 migration preserving the threading model, fixing the race condition:

```csharp
public class EventProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private readonly ManualResetEvent _newEvent = new(false);
    private readonly Queue<string> _queue = new();
    private readonly object _lock = new();
    private readonly CancellationTokenSource _cts = new();
    private Thread? _thread;

    public void Start()
    {
        _thread = new Thread(RunLoop) { IsBackground = true };
        _thread.Start();
    }

    private void RunLoop()
    {
        var handles = new WaitHandle[] { _newEvent, _cts.Token.WaitHandle };

        while (!_cts.Token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            // Blocks until either a new event arrives OR cancellation is requested
            int signaled = WaitHandle.WaitAny(handles);
            if (signaled == 1) // cancellation handle
                break;

            _newEvent.Reset();

            // Drain all queued items (fixes the race condition)
            while (true)
            {
                string? item;
                lock (_lock)
                {
                    if (_queue.Count == 0) break;
                    item = _queue.Dequeue();
                }
                Handle(item);
            }
        }
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item)
    {
        lock (_lock) { _queue.Enqueue(item); }
        _newEvent.Set();
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        _cts.Cancel();            // wakes WaitAny via token.WaitHandle
        _thread?.Join(5000);      // wait for clean exit
        // No Thread.Abort — if it hasn't exited, it will on next checkpoint
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts.Dispose();
        _newEvent.Dispose();
    }

    private void Handle(string item) { /* ... */ }
}
```

## Recommended: Modern Idiomatic Version (Channel\<T\>)

`Channel<T>` replaces the manual queue + event + lock entirely:

```csharp
public class EventProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private readonly Channel<string> _channel = Channel.CreateUnbounded<string>();
    private readonly CancellationTokenSource _cts = new();
    private Task? _worker;

    public void Start()
    {
        _worker = Task.Run(() => RunLoopAsync(_cts.Token));
    }

    private async Task RunLoopAsync(CancellationToken token)
    {
        try
        {
            await foreach (var item in _channel.Reader.ReadAllAsync(token))
            {
                Handle(item);
            }
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException)
        {
            // Expected on shutdown — don't propagate
        }
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item)
    {
        _channel.Writer.TryWrite(item);
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        _channel.Writer.Complete();   // signal no more items
        _cts.Cancel();                // interrupt if blocked on empty channel
        _worker?.Wait(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts.Dispose();
    }

    private void Handle(string item) { /* ... */ }
}
```

## Key Migration Pitfalls

| Pitfall | What happens | Fix |
|---------|-------------|-----|
| Keeping `Thread.Abort()` | `PlatformNotSupportedException` at runtime | Replace with `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()` |
| Using `WaitOne()` without token | Thread can't be woken for shutdown | Use `WaitHandle.WaitAny` with `token.WaitHandle` |
| Not draining the queue per wake | Items pile up, only 1 processed per signal | Loop until queue is empty after each wake |
| Not disposing `CancellationTokenSource` | Timer/callback leak | Implement `IDisposable`, wrap in `using` |
| Catching `OperationCanceledException` and retrying | Infinite loop on shutdown | Only catch at the top-level orchestrator; let it end the loop |
| Assuming cancellation is instant | `Handle(item)` won't be interrupted mid-execution | Pass `CancellationToken` into `Handle` if it does long work |

The **Channel\<T\> version** is strongly recommended — it eliminates the manual synchronization entirely, is naturally async, and is the idiomatic .NET 8 pattern for producer-consumer queues.
